The paper deals with the problem of demand privacy in coded caching, which involves information theory and cryptography (cs.IT), distributed computing (cs.DC), and security and privacy (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the memory-rate trade-off, which is a fundamental concept in coding theory (cs.CC) and has applications in various fields such as communication networks and distributed storage systems. Finally, the paper presents a specific case study for the demand-private coded caching problem for $K=2$ users, $N=2$ files, which can be considered as a subfield of information theory and coding theory (cs.SI).
